<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-109-111 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 960 794</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  July 8 1991 v8 n27 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>IBM, Apple deal a boon for net users. (IBM and Apple announceplans to jointly develop operating systems)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Desmond, Paul.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>IBM and Apple have announced plans to jointly develop a variety ofsystems and connectivity software, including products that willbenefit network users by simplifying the integration ofMacintoshes into IBM-based environments.andP;  The two companies willcreate an object-oriented operating system for the POWER PCreduced-instruction-set computer (RISC) processor, which IBM willwork with Motorola Inc to develop.andP;  Apple and IBM have outlined atwo-pronged networking strategy that includes joint development,marketing and support of products enhancing Mac-to-IBMconnectivity and the creation of an enhanced version of IBM's AIXUnix implementation that will run Mac applications.andP;  The new AIXwill use the Open Software Foundation Motif graphical interface,and the upcoming object-oriented product may also simplifymultivendor networking by providing application portability.andO;Analysts say that the alliance is a good move, and users expressenthusiasm.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Apple Computer Inc. (Product development)International Business Machines Corp. (Product development).andO;Ticker:    IBM; AAPL.andO;Topic:     Computer industryUnixCooperative AgreementProduct DevelopmentOperating systemsUser NeedsLocal Area NetworksObject-Oriented ProgrammingConnectivity.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>